-- Ablynx, Atlantia, BP, Novartis, Vodafone Group: European Equity Preview
-- Lu Wang
-- 2010-07-13T04:00:02Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-12/ablynx-atlantia-bp-novartis-vodafone-group-european-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are from the last close.  
 The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  gained 0.4 percent to 251.18.
The  Stoxx 50 Index  rose 0.5 percent to 2,442.89. The  Euro Stoxx
50 Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro, advanced 0.2
percent to 2,686.09.  
 Ablynx NV  (ABLX BB): Novartis AG (NOVN VX) agreed to pay
the Belgian developer of drugs based on antibodies found in
llamas 1 million euros for the right to develop and market two
undisclosed experimental treatments included in a 2005 alliance.
Ablynx will also be eligible for milestone payments and
royalties on potential sales of the two medicines. Ablynx
dropped 0.3 percent to 7.42 euros. Novartis gained 0.4 percent
to 52.45 Swiss francs.  
 Atlantia SpA  (ATL IM),  Societa Iniziative Autostradali e
Servizi SpA  (SIS IM): The two Italian highway companies plan to
merge their concessionaire units in Chile and may list shares in
the joint venture, according to two separate statements.
Altantia fell 0.1 percent to 15.5 euros. SIAS rose 0.9 percent
to 7.2 euros.  
 BP Plc  (BP/ LN): The largest producer of oil and natural
gas in the U.S. delayed drilling its first well at the Liberty
project in Alaska until next year. The shares advanced 9.4
percent to 398.95 pence.  
 Vodafone Group Plc  (VOD LN): The world’s biggest mobile-
phone operator and Telefonica SA’s O2 unit said proposed cuts in
some U.K. mobile-phone fees may lead to higher charges for
handsets and calls, forcing as many as 4 million customers to
give up their phones. The shares fell 0.1 percent to 143.4
pence.  
 VTG AG  (VT9 GR): The rail logistics company entered the
grain transport market after buying about 1,100 grain silo
wagons from Ermewa Ferroviaire SAS and a 75 percent stake in the
French rail logistics company TMF SA. The purchase price remains
confidential, VTG said. The fell 0.3 percent to 12.06 euros.  
